The board may refuse to issue a credential, or may suspend, revoke, impose probationary conditions upon, impose an administrative fine, or issue a written reprimand or admonishment if the credential holder has:
Committed a dishonest or corrupt act. If the act is a crime, conviction in a criminal proceeding shall not be a condition precedent to disciplinary action. Upon conviction of the crime, the judgment and sentence are presumptive evidence at the ensuing disciplinary hearing of the guilt of the credential holder or applicant. Conviction includes all instances in which a plea of no contest is the basis of the conviction;
Misrepresented or concealed a material fact in obtaining or reinstating a credential;
Committed any unfair, false, misleading, or deceptive act or practice;
Been incompetent or negligent in the activities he has undertaken within his or her practice;
Violated any state statute or administrative regulation promulgated pursuant to KRS 335.500 to 335.599;
Failed to comply with an order issued by the board or an assurance of voluntary compliance;
Violated the code of ethics; or
Violated any applicable provisions of federal or state law.
